ce:section.ce:para:
The results reveal a marked contrast between the two charging phases. Thus, during fast charging, energy losses (E

                           lost
                        ) remain relatively low and stable, ranging from 144.69 Wh (on the day with the lowest PSH value) to 593.68 Wh (441.75 Wh on average). These values are justified by a slight overestimation of the model obtained in [45]. In contrast, during slow charging, losses increased drastically to an average value of 4443.13 Wh, ranging from 2558.04 Wh to 6859.23 Wh (on the days with the lowest and highest PSH values, respectively). This substantial difference underscores the inefficiency of the system during the slow charging phase. These results highlight the importance of ensuring that the system can store or use the full energy capacity that the PV field could generate at MPPT, enabling more energy to supply loads.

The contrast between the two charging phases is further emphasized by the values for energy stored in the battery (E

                           LIB
                        ), which show values of (7750.42 ± 611.00) Wh during fast charge versus (232.32 ± 154.49) Wh for slow charge (expressed as mean ± SD). This discrepancy highlights the impact of curtailment, which refers to the deliberate reduction of PV power output due to constraints in the system's storage capacity or its ability to utilize the available energy. During the slow charging phase, a considerable amount of solar energy that could have been harnessed is lost (not generated), as the system cannot store it or redirect it to other uses. As a result, the PV array operates significantly below its potential, especially under high irradiance conditions, when curtailment becomes more pronounced during the final part of the charging process.
